  <section xml:id="Chapter_01-units">
    <title>Units</title>
    <objectives>
      <ul>
        <li>What are the similarities and differences between the SI and US Customary Unity Systems?</li>
        <li>How do you convert a value into different units?</li>
        <li>When a Statics problem lists the pounds [lb] of a body, is this referring to pounds-force [lbf] or pounds-mass [lbm]?</li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
    <p>Quantities used in engineering usually consist of a numeric value and an associated unit. The value by itself is meaningless. When discussing a quantity you must always include the associated unit, except when the correct unit is <sq>no units.</sq>
    </p>
    <p>In the United States two primary unit systems are commonly in use, the International System of Units and the US Customary System.  Although in statics we will be most concerned with force and length and less so with other units, as an engineer you should be comfortable using any unit in either system.</p>
    <p>The International System of Units, SI, an abbrivation for the French <foreign>Système international (d'unités)</foreign> is the modern form of the metric system and is the most widely used system of measurement worldwide. It comprises a coherent system of units of measurement built on seven base units: the second, meter, kilogram, ampere, kelvin, mole, candela.  In statics, the only the first three base units are used.   All other units required are derived from combinations of the base units.  Prefixes to unit names are used to specify the base-10 multiple of the original unit.  </p>
    <p>The United States customary system was developed from the measurement system in use in the British Empire before the US became an independent country. However, the United Kingdom’s system of measures was overhauled in 1824 to create the Imperial system, changing the definitions of some units. Therefore, while many US units are similar to their Imperial counterparts, there are significant differences between the systems. The base units in the customary system for time, distance, and mass are the second, foot, and slug. </p>
    <p> Force is related to mass and acceleration by Newton’s second law <men>F = ma</men>, so force has the units of mass <m>[m]</m> multiplied by length <m>[L]</m> divided by time <m>[t]</m> squared <me>F= [m L/t^2]</me>.</p>
    <p>In SI system, the unit of force is the newton, abbreviated N, and the unit of mass is the kilogram, abbreviated kg. One newton, is the force which, when applied to a one kilogram mass causes it to accelerate at a rate of <m>\aSI{1}</m>. One newton is equal to <m>\mathrm{1\ kg \cdot m}/\mathrm{s}^2</m>.</p>
    <p>In US Customary units, the unit of force is the pound-force, abreviated  <m>\mathrm{lbf}, </m> or pound for short, and the unit of mass is the slug. In this system, one pound of force will accelerate a mass of one slug at <m>\aUS{1}</m>, so one pound-force  is equal to <m>\mathrm{1\ slug \cdot ft}/\mathrm{s}^2</m>.  On earth, a 1 slug mass weighs <m>\lbf{32.2}</m>. </p>
    <p>You may ocasionally see mass expessed in units of pounds-mass, rather than in slugs.  The advantage of this unit choice is that a <m>\lbm{1}</m> mass weighs <m>\lbf{1}</m> on earth, meaining that <m>g = \aUS{1}</m>.</p>
